The market and the equilibrium price

  • buyers and sellers come together and interact in a market to buy corn (as an example)

  • the price that equates supply and demand together is called the equlibrium price.

  • at the equilibrium, there is one price, say \(P^{*}\) that makes quantity demanded equal to the quantity supplied.

    • we also say that the market clears at the equilibrium price.

  • if the price is above the equilibrium price, then there will be an excess supply. Similarly, if the actual price is below the equilibrium price, sellers will wait before the price moves up to sell.

  • here, the assumption is that all of the corn in the market is identical (the same)

Putting the demand and supply together

Figure 3. Demand and Supply together

  • Note that \(P^{*}\) is $8. At price below $8, there will be more buyers in the market, the market will suffer from shortage.

  • At price above $8, the market will have excess supply

  • The market clears at $8, where the equilibrium quantity \(Q^{*}=25\).

Price taking

  • In the second hand book market, individual students have to accept the prevailing equilibrium price, determined by the demand and supply.

  • If you (as a seller) are asking for a higher price, me (as a buyer) will move to a different seller who is charging an equilibrium price.

  • In this sense, sellers are price takers. However, we have seen where market participants are not price takers (for example monopolists set their own price)

    • if you have a differentiated goods with no close substitute then you gain market power, which gives liberty to set pries.

  • However, if there are a lot of sellers and buyers for one identical type of product, the participants will just take the market price.

  • The equilibrium in this kind of market is known as a competitive equilibrium.

Price-taking firms

  • In lecture 8 we saw how firms choose their price and quantity when producing differentiated products (cars)

  • However, if the firms are producing identical products, then firms will be a price taker in the market

  • Lets explore how a price taking firm behaves. Say, you own a bakery store in a city where there are many bakeries. The market demand curve for bread is

Figure 5. Market demand for bread

  • As a baker, you are deciding what price to charge. Say, your neighboring bakeries are selling a identical loaves for 2.35 and if this is a market price, you wont be able to sell for a higher price than 2.35. Why?

Firms decision in a competitive market

  • Note that as a baker (among many other bakers selling identical product), you will be a price-taker.
    • So, youll set 2.35 for a loaf of bread.
  • Figure 6 shows your marginal cost and average cost curves. The average cost includes the opportunity cost of having a capital (eg. an oven to bake bread)

Figure 6. Firms decision

  • The average cost curve shows the zero economic profit (if price is equal to AC, economic profit is zero)
    • The marginal cost curve (MC) intersects AC at the lowest point
    • MC intersects isoprofit curves at the lowest point as well
  • Here, you are a price taker, so any point below the market price is feasible in Figure 6.
    • Again this is a constrained maximization problem, except that the firms demand curve is flat. This means that for price greater than \(P^{*}\) youll have no customers but for price less than \(P^{*}\) you can sell as much as you want.
  • In this case, the profit maximization price is \(P^{*}\), when the firms demand curve is tangential to the isoprofit line.
    • This is also when \(P^{*}\) is equal to MC
  • So one important realization is that at the profit maximization point, \(P^{*}=MC\).
    • This is because if \(P>MC\) one should sell more to increase profit
    • if \(P<MC\), one should decrease selling
  • Hence, A price-taking firm maximizes profit by choosing a quantity where the marginal cost is equal to the market price (MC = P) and selling at the market price P.

As the market price changes

  • Your firm will react to changes in the market price by picking an output such that price (P*)=MC.

Figure 7. Firms decision

Market Supply and Equilibrium

  • Each baker will have its own supply curve. Lets suppose that there are 50 bakeries in the market. If you add the total quantity that all the bakers will supply at the given price, you get the market supply curve. This is shown in Figure 8.

Figure 8. Market Supply Curve

  • if the market price is 2.75, total market supply is 7,000.
    • The cost of producing one more loaf is 2.75, which is the marginal cost
    • Hence, the marginal cost is also the supply curve

      Figure 9. Equilibrium in the market for bread

  • Figure 9 shows the demand and supply for the bread market as a whole
  • The equilibrium market price is 2.00, and 5,000 loaves are traded.
    • From Figure 8, you should find that the avereage cost per loaf at 5,000 loaves is less than 2.00. This means that the bakery owners are receiving economic rents.
    • Economic rent is likely to attract other ponteial bakers into the bakery market.

Changes in Demand and Supply

  • In the second hand book market, the buyers are new students taking the course and sellers are older students who finished the course

Figure 11. A new equilibrium point

  • The supply and the older demand curve sets the price at \(\$8\).

  • Say, the course got more popular one semester.

    • This shifts the demand to the right (new demand curve), which gives the equilibrium price of \(\$10\).

  • When we say increase in demand, its important to be careful about exactly what we mean:

    • Demand is higher at each possible price, so the demand curve has shifted.
    • In response to this shift there is a change in the price.
    • This leads to an increase in the quantity supplied.
    • This change is a movement along the supply curve.
    • But the supply curve itself has not shifted (the number of sellers and their reserve prices have not changed), so we do not call this an increase in supply.

  • In Figure 11, an increase in demand raised both equilibrium price and quantity.

Figure 12. A new equilibrium point due to shift in supply

  • Increase in supply due to an increased productivity (new and improved machine) shifts the supply to the right in Figure 12.
    • Note that this lowers the equilibrium price but increases quantity.
